:::summary
Aesthetics is the branch of philosophy concerned with beauty, art, and taste — asking what makes something beautiful, what art is and why it matters, and whether aesthetic judgments are objective or merely subjective. From Plato's suspicion of poetry to Kant's analysis of the sublime, aesthetics has grappled with the deepest questions about human experience and the value of the beautiful.
:::

